==English==

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/ə.ˈkleɪm/|lang=en}}
* {{rhymes|eɪm|lang=en}}

===Etymology 1===
* First attested in the early 14th century.
* {{sense|to applaud}} First attested in the 1630's.
* From {{etyl|la|en}} {{m|la|acclāmō||raise a cry at; applaud}}, formed from {{m|la|ad-}} + {{m|la|clāmō||cry out, shout}}.

====Verb====
{{en-verb}}

# {{label|en|archaic|transitive}} To [[shout]]; to [[call out]].
# {{label|en|intransitive}} To shout approval; to express great [[approval]].
#* '''1911''', {{w|Saki}}, ''The Chronicles of Clovis''
#*: The design, when finally developed, was a slight disappointment to Monsieur Deplis, who had suspected Icarus of being a fortress taken by Wallenstein in the Thirty Years' War, but he was more than satisfied with the execution of the work, which was '''acclaimed''' by all who had the privilege of seeing it as Pincini's masterpiece.
# {{label|en|transitive|rare}} To [[salute]] or [[praise]] with great approval; to [[compliment]]; to [[applaud]]; to [[welcome]] enthusiastically.
#* A glad '''acclaiming''' train. - Thomson
# {{label|en|transitive|obsolete}} To [[claim]].
# {{label|en|transitive}} To [[declare]] by [[acclamations]].
#* While the shouting crowd / '''Acclaims''' thee king of traitors. - Smollett
# {{label|en|Canada|politics}} To elect to an office by having no opposition.

